REVENUES

SPACE AND COMMUNICATIONS

SEGMENT REVENUES WERE $11.0 BILLION IN 2002, COMPARED WITH $10.4 BILLION IN 2001

AND $8.0 BILLION IN 2000. THE SEGMENT REMAINS BROADLY DIVERSIFIED. THE

CONTRIBUTORS TO 2002 SPACE AND COMMUNICATIONS SEGMENT REVENUES INCLUDED FIVE

MARKET SEGMENTS: INTEGRATED BATTLESPACE, MISSILE DEFENSE, HUMAN SPACE FLIGHT AND

EXPLORATION, LAUNCH AND SATELLITE AND HOMELAND SECURITY. THE INCREASE IN

REVENUES FROM 2001 TO 2002 WAS PRIMARILY DUE TO INCREASED ACTIVITY IN MISSILE

DEFENSE OFFSET BY DECREASES IN LAUNCH AND SATELLITE DUE TO CONTINUED MARKET

DOWNTURN. 2001 REVENUES WERE HIGHER THAN 2000 REVENUES DUE PRIMARILY TO

INCREASED ACTIVITY ON INTEGRATED BATTLESPACE PROGRAMS AND THE ACQUISITION OF

BOEING SATELLITE SYSTEMS (BSS) IN OCTOBER 2000.

